<activity xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="act-1-2-2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider a moving object whose position function is given by <m>s(t) = t^2</m>,
      where <m>s</m> is measured in meters and <m>t</m> is measured in minutes.
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol label="a.">
        <li>
          <p>
            Determine the most simplified expression for the average velocity of the object on the interval
            <m>[3, 3+h]</m>, where <m>h \gt 0</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Determine the average velocity of the object on the interval <m>[3,3.2]</m>.
            Include units on your answer.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>Determine the instantaneous velocity of the object when <m>t = 3</m>.
          Include units on your answer.</li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      <ol label="a.">
        <li><m>s(3+h) = (3+h)^2</m>.</li>

        <li>Recall that <m>AV_{[a,b]} = \frac{s(b)-s(a)}{b-a}</m>.</li>

        <li>Consider <m>\lim_{h \to 0} \frac{s(3+h)-s(3)}{h}</m> and use your work in (a).</li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </hint>
  <answer>
    <p>
      <ol label="a.">
        <li><m>6 + h</m>.</li>

        <li><m>6.2</m> meters/min.</li>

        <li><m>6</m> meters per minute.</li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </answer>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <ol label="a.">
        <li>Observe that <m>AV_{[3, 3+h]} =  \frac{s(3+h)-s(3)}{h} = \frac{(3+h)^2 - 3^2}{h} = \frac{9 + 6h + h^2 - 9}{h} = \frac{6h + h^2}{h} = \frac{h(6 + h)}{h} = 6 + h</m>.</li>

        <li>Using the expression just found in (a) with <m>h = 0.2</m>,
          <m>AV_{[3,3.2]} = 6 + 0.2 = 6.2</m> meters/min.</li>

        <li>Taking the limit of average velocity and using our work from (a),
          we find that
          <me>
            IV_{t = 3} = \lim_{h \to 0} AV_{[3, 3+h]} = \lim_{h \to 0} 6+h = 6
          </me>,
          so the instantaneous velocity of the object when <m>t = 3</m> is 6 meters per minute.</li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</activity>

